benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/tags - Remove tags from bundle

covered: Valid Deletion: TC01 (remove all tags), TC02 (remove specific tags), TC03 (headers present), TC04 (no tags), TC12/TC18 (large tag sets and performance scenarios), TC15 (concurrency), TC16 (regression empty tagDef), TC17 (integration/data consistency), TC10 (service unavailable), TC06 (non-existent bundleId), TC07 (invalid tagDef), TC08 (missing required header), TC09 (unauthorized), TC11 (extra unexpected query param), TC13 (partial valid/invalid tagDef), TC14 (header injection checks), TC19 (accessibility of error responses)
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination handling for large result sets or listing tags with pagination semantics.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios testing caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) for DELETE responses.
Rate Limiting: No tests cover rate limiting or throttling behavior under bursty DELETE requests.
Soft Deletes: No explicit test clarifying whether deletions are soft or hard (not clearly addressed in scenarios).
Authorization depth: While there are tests for missing header and unauthorized user, broader role-based authorization boundaries and 403 scenarios are not explicitly covered.
Edge-case timing/timeout variations beyond the explicit 504/timeout scenario (TC18) are not explored.
recommendations: Add pagination-focused tests for GET-like semantics on tag payloads or for listing after deletions if such endpoints exist, to validate handling of large datasets.
Add caching tests to verify presence and behavior of ETag/Cache-Control headers for DELETE or related GETs, ensuring correct cache invalidation semantics.
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests (e.g., bursts beyond a threshold) to verify graceful degradation or appropriate 429 responses.
Clarify and test soft-delete behavior if applicable by the API design; include scenarios asserting whether tags are physically removed or merely unlinked.
Expand authorization testing to include 403 Forbidden scenarios for users with insufficient permissions, and validate broader RBAC implications beyond “unauthorized” (401).
Add additional timeout scenarios with varying server load or longer operation times to validate graceful fallback beyond the 504/204 dichotomy.
